##Wuhan driver WHO VOLUNTEERS TO PICK UP DOCTORS: poor and small, I can do nothing but drive

MICRO-SIGNAL ESQUIRECN

Function description, fashion makes sir, Sir defines fashion.

Dictation by Huang Xiaomin

Interview with Zhang Jin

Contacted Huang Xiaomin, it was more than 8:00 pm on February 2, he had just coordinated a batch of materials sent to the hospital back home. There was a cough on the other end of the phone.

Huang Xiaomin, 38, is a marketing associate at Nanguo real estate. On January 23, Wuhan 123 set up a volunteer convoy, 24 began to pick up medical staff to work, 28, because the volunteer team lack of protective materials, there are security risks, he decided to stop the operation. In 11 days, he set up five wechat volunteer groups (three disbanded due to lack of protective equipment) , summoned 174 drivers and transported more than 200 medical staff to and from work. After the suspension, he did not stay at home, still running around, for the hospital, volunteers to raise all kinds of supplies.

Over the course of 11 days, Huang and his friends witnessed a lot of fear and courage, and they were scared, but wanted to prove that the Wuhan people were not all deserters.

During the interview, a faint cough could be heard all along. Huang Xiaomin said nothing, joking that he was the biggest "drug source. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Here's what he said:

From the Southern Center to my home, will pass 4 hospitals, night work back home I often see some medical staff after the night shift after the car is very difficult, at that time I think I can actually pass a foot.

In December, news began trickling in that someone had contracted pneumonia and there was a problem with the south China Seafood Market, but it didn't matter because the government had come out and said the disease would not be passed from person to person. In January of this year, as word spread, I became wary. In 2003, I was in college: Zhongnan University of Economics and Law, Wuhan was not an epidemic area at that time, but we also knew from the news that many SARS survivors were suffering. At that time, it was rumored that this pneumonia was a bit like SARS, i guess it's one of those "if you're cured, you're half dead" kind of things, you know, and you start taking precautions, but you don't really care.

On the 18th, 12 members of my extended family gathered for a New Year's Eve dinner in the heart of southern Florida, where I work. That day, the Baibu Pavilion Community also held a banquet for 10,000 people. Oh!

Although the news is not blocked, but the people still have a way to inquire about, the news is sealed. On January 20, I saw on the Internet that a woman who had come to Wuhan had died. I started to panic and immediately told my family and colleagues to wear a mask. But not many people wear them. Not many people wear them at the mall where I work.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
So on January 21, I took a selfie wearing a gas mask that I wore to play Mahjong. I usually never smoke, also can not smell, smell very uncomfortable, brothers play Mahjong like smoking, I wear this, they also laugh at me: afraid of death. I'm really scared of dying.

In the early morning of January 23, Wuhan announced the closure of the city, the city bus stop, I quickly thought of them (medical staff) how to work? The same night on the establishment of a "Wuhan Doctor Travel Mutual Help Group" , to find colleagues, students and Party B partner together to do driver volunteers. Friends circle a hair, that night a lot of people scan code in. Now that I think about it, this is probably one of the most successful head-grabbing campaigns I've ever done? In fact, I also want to leave Wuhan that day, the highway has not been completely closed, I have time to go. But I am the only strong man in the family, grandma 93 years old, aunt 62 years old, parents 64 years old, cousins and the like are not in Wuhan, in case the elderly have something, what should I do? So I brought my parents over early in the morning.

With more and more dedicated volunteers joining, the 123 volunteer fleet already has more than 100 drivers, and from January 24 to 28, we transport about 200 medical staff to and from work every day. But now it's gone. No more. The situation in Wuhan is getting worse and worse. I can not bear the responsibility.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Named "123 motorcade" because of the date of the closure of the city and because "1,2,3" is like a signal to start action, quick response, and later I found that and Wuhan's "Guan De Kuan" quite homophonic. Sometimes, the rest of us, we manage a lot.

On the night of the 23rd, I got a job. I didn't have a hat and goggles at first, so I put on my swimming cap and goggles and went for it. Later, the paramedic in my car said to me, "your precautions aren't working. There's GonNa be problems. ". A young nurse gave me a splash mask, volunteers brought us isolation suits, face masks, and a small convenience store where they got into 84's supply of disinfectant and reserved two cases specifically for us. We're getting better equipped. A 62-year-old doctor who was rehired told me that he had to ride his bike to work for two hours and a quarter before our motorcade picked him up.

My wife took her 1-year-old daughter home to yellowstone for the New Year before she closed the city. On the 23rd, I told her on Wechat that I wanted to be a motorcade. She was silent for a few minutes. Then I told her a lot about the condition of the medical staff: After working all night, I had to wait for a bus, and only buses are available in big hospitals, the Community Health Service didn't have... they had to walk two or three hours to get home. And then she said, you go ahead. I couldn't go to the front line, I couldn't go to the construction site to build a hospital, so I wanted to do one little thing: drive.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Some drivers are out of the wife, my classmates let me send friends circle do not mention him, he is to tell his wife is out playing Mahjong, fishing, Mahjong partners are very healthy, wearing N95 mask.

When I drive, I open half of the windows, because I remember SARS said that at that time to frequent ventilation, frequent ventilation, so I drive every day to open the windows, Wuhan these days is still quite cold. My cough could be from a cold. I hope so.

For about the third time, I picked up two nurses from the Lake district behind Wuhan Central Hospital, both of whom were post-'95. One of the nurses told me that the first confirmed case was in her ward, bed 27, and that she had taken care of it several times. I asked her if she was scared? She said, "of course I'm scared. ". Then we were silent, not knowing what to say.

The paramedics are really tired and it's not easy. One morning at 7:00, I picked up a nurse from work, and she got in the car and fell asleep in the back seat. Luckily I knew where she lived. And I was driving and I was thinking, how tired is this? To sleep in a strange man's car? I felt very sad... after going back, I announced a rule in the group of drivers: All drivers must give me three cards (ID card, driver's license, driving license) a single (insurance policy) , or kick the group. It's the least I can do for the paramedics. A doctor asked us to pick up his father, because he and his father have to go to a different hospital services, he can not take care of his father to work.

A young Concorde nurse, who was not in the respiratory infection department, said she would volunteer to go to the front when Vulcan and thor hospitals were built.

When many doctors and nurses get off the bus, they drop 100 yuan in cash or send red envelopes on Wechat. We don't accept them. Sometimes I give them red envelopes. Tell them to refuel.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
For protection, we asked the paramedics to talk to the driver as little as possible, and we were strangers and it was always quiet on the bus. I'll talk to them at the Red Light. I asked a nurse what she wanted to do when the outbreak was over? She said she wanted a good drink of water and 48 hours of sleep. Because they always wear protective clothing, supplies are scarce, dare not drink water a day.

In addition to picking up and dropping off medical staff, I, as the leader of the volunteer convoy, would try my best to raise supplies, take them to the hospital, and hand them out to volunteers. So my home is like a transit station, there are a lot of things, often people come to our home to take things. Everyone wore masks and didn't recognize each other. Everyone spoke little but moved quickly.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the 25th, I was delivering supplies to the Lake district behind Wuhan Central Hospital, and I got some alcohol, so I thought I'd drop it off and give them a hand. There were seven or eight nurses at the emergency desk, and I said, "Hi, I'm a volunteer named Huang Xiaomin, and I'm here to donate two cases of alcohol. " The nurse who was waiting for me was confused and said, "wait a minute, I'll go and find our head nurse. I was standing in the emergency room, surrounded by patients.

On the left, a nurse soothed a high-risk patient, who could not be diagnosed without a test kit. The nurse consoled him, "calm down, " and he shouted in Wuhan, "How can I calm down? On the right is a line of people waiting to see a doctor. There were a lot of people sitting on the floor, too, because the traffic in the city was stopped, a lot of people had to walk an hour or two to get to the hospital, and the emergency room didn't have so many stools, so they couldn't stand and had to sit on the floor.

For a moment, I felt really pathetic and small, and there was nothing I could do but drive. I left the alcohol on the ER table before the head nurse came. I can't stay in that environment. I have to go.

On the longest day, I wore the same gloves for six hours and a protective suit for 13 hours. About 11 trips back and forth, about 20 paramedics. Wuhan University. It's really big. At this point, I wish I had a smaller city.

I recently more than 1200 people in Wechat, most of them do not know, but everyone is really warm-hearted, is there a feeling? The virus has been closing in on us like crazy this month.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the 27th, there was a single from the Eighth Hospital of Wuhan to Jiangxia District, the whole journey is 30 kilometers. I was worried that no one would pick up the single at first, but soon a driver said: no one, I'll go! On the 24th, when the Group started picking up and dropping off, I told the driver in the group that you were in trouble, and I offered you 20 bucks a pop, but no one asked me for it. Unlike Didi, which subsidizes more than 1,000 drivers a day, we pay for our own gas.

The Cooperation Design Company has designed the team logo for the team free of charge, the logistics volunteers have printed it, everyone goes to get it separately, stick it under the car windshield, the traffic police will see our sign and let it pass.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The emergency nurse at the Central Hospital said that there was a newly married couple who had just finished decorating their wedding room in a neighborhood near the Lake district behind the Central Hospital. They gave the new room to the medical staff free of charge and refused to accept even a deposit, i don't even think I can do that.

As a captain, I sometimes have to comfort some of my teammates in the group, so I'm mostly optimistic. But sometimes, I fall apart.

On January 28, the outbreak began, with 800 new cases confirmed in Wuhan. I was actually really happy that day, because I got four boxes of isolation suits, 200 of them, and I wanted to rush them to the hospital and the community. But then I saw on my phone that the number of diagnoses was increasing, and I started to worry. I felt so stressed that I cried twice. I started the 123rd, but I couldn't take responsibility for the volunteers'lives, so I wrote a friend's letter to the driver and a letter to the paramedic. One by one, I explained to the medical staff: We volunteers have no protection, so from January 29th, when we can get EN14126type4 or higher suits and N95 masks, if the city still needs us, we stop taking orders, we'll continue to transport the paramedics.

On the afternoon of the 30th, I got 10 more cases of alcohol, liquid gold! I was so excited that I posted a friend's message: "It's better to see alcohol than wine. " Then I got a message from a doctor at the eighth hospital. I can't remember if I picked him up or dropped him off. "Can you send us some alcohol? We're running low on supplies. "Then he sent me a picture of his department using paper bags and duct tape to make their own protective masks. I knew there was a shortage of supplies, but I didn't expect such a shortage!

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"where are our supplies? Who can tell me? "At that moment, I really can not stand, squatting on the ground cried a meal, the upper half of the isolation suit is all wet.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Recently, my mentality has been changing, at first (the night of the 23rd) I did not want anything, I just want to help the medical staff, I am calm. The number of patients began to increase on the 24th, I began to get excited, after all, my job is to do marketing, 28th I really scared, very difficult, I am just an ordinary person, no money no status does not matter. Number 30 is in complete collapse, seeing our supplies being piled up by the red club! Now that I'm at peace again, I think I can do a little bit. When this is over, I just want to drive back to yellowstone and hug my daughter, and I really miss her. I would also like to keep this group of 123 volunteers to help the disabled, the elderly..

I am not as great as everyone said, brave, I just want to prove a point: Wuhan people are not all that everyone said are deserters, to escape the source of infection, airdropped to the world; There are soldiers like us who don't even have weapons.
